  "prompt": "Why did oil prices fall again in 2015?",
  "response": "In 2015, oil prices fell significantly due to several key factors:\n\n1. Oversupply in the global oil market: OPEC, particularly Saudi Arabia, continued to produce oil at high levels despite falling prices, which increased global supply.\n\n2. Reduced demand: Slower economic growth, especially in China, led to lower global oil consumption.\n\n3. Iran nuclear deal: The agreement lifted sanctions on Iran, allowing the country to increase its oil exports and add more supply to the market.\n\n4. U.S. shale oil production: Despite lower prices, American shale oil producers continued to pump oil, maintaining high production levels.\n\n5. Strong U.S. dollar: Oil is priced in dollars, and a stronger dollar made oil more expensive for buyers using other currencies, reducing demand.\n\nThese factors combined to push oil prices down, with crude oil prices falling from over $100 per barrel in mid-2014 to around $35-$40 per barrel by early 2016.",
